Diabetes in Children

Purpose

There is a stark increase in E10-E14 coded deaths in 2022. It is unknown whether this is an algorithmic change or an actual change in DNF input. We aim to investigate the multiple cause codes among final cause E10-E14 codes among 0-4 age group.

A priori knowledge

  • Diabetes is rare in children under 5 years old.
  • COVID-19 was known to unmask diabetes in some cases.
  • MIS-C (Multi system inflammatory syndrome in children) is a known complication of COVID-19 infection in children, and has been associated with new onset diabetes in some cases.
  • DKA (diabetic ketoacidosis) is a known complication of diabetes, and can be a presenting feature of new onset diabetes.

Figure 1 shows that the reported birth year of E10-E14 coded deaths in 0-4 year olds is concentrated in 2018-2021, with very few deaths reported in children born before 2018. Unsure what systematic errors in birth year reporting there may be

Figure 2 shows that there is a marked increase in E10-E14 coded deaths in 0-4 year olds and 5-39 year olds in 2022 (purple).

Table 1 shows the immediate cause codes among E10-E14 coded deaths in 0-4 year olds from 2019 to 2022. The most common immediate cause codes are I149 (I14.9 - Unspecified diabetes mellitus Without complications), Cause B and Cause C are similar but not reported here.

Figure 3 shows the trends of the top 5 immediate cause codes among E10-E14 coded deaths in 0-4 year olds from 2019 to 2022.

Figure 4 shows generally shows WC as being well-behaved.

Immediate cause code I149 (I14.9 - Unspecified diabetes mellitus Without complications) was coded as immediate cause more in 2022 than in previous years among 0-4 year olds. It is also noted in 5-39 years.
